1.Introduction

R has many packages to make graphs. The default one is a option, but ggplot is one of the most powerful tools. With ggplot2, it is easy to apply multiple graphs by learning one.

This document is designed for the student association Turing tutorial at Erasmus University Rotterdam. Thanks for the director of Turing, George, who provided a comprehensive notebook to me as reference.

2. Prerequisites

2.1 GGplot2 package

GGplot2 is one of the core members of the tidyverse. We first need to install and load tidyverse package.

We are going to use mpg data frame, which is built-in data in ggplot2. mpg contains observations collected by the US Environmental Protection Agency on 38 models of car. Run the code block below to get an idea of the content of the mpg data set.

We can see that among variables in mpg are:

  1. displ:a cars engine size, in litres.
  2. hwy: a cars fuel efficiency on the highway, in miles per gallon (mpg). A car with a low fuel efficiency consumes more fuel than a car with a high fuel efficiency when they travel the same distance.

3. Different plots

We will draw different plots and interpret them. To be noticed, it is easy to plot, but it is not easy to required data format. E.g. when drawing a bar chart, we need to deal with data in advance. We will see later on.

3.1 A simple ggplot

ggplot(mpg, aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point()

From the plot, we see a negative relationship between engine size(displ) and fuel efficiency(hwy). That is, the bigger the car, the more fuel will be used.

3.1.1 Fill color for the simple plot

We can provide more information by fill the colors for different types of car.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

We can see from this plot that bigger cars like suv consume more fuel(not so efficient on high way). Compact and Subcompact models are relatively more efficient.

3.1.1 Change the points size for the simple plot

In the above example, we use colors to identify different fuel-efficiency for different car models. We may also use different point sizes to identify them. Or both color and sizes?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))

3.1.1 Change the transparency for the simple plot

To use transparency to identify different fuel-efficiency for different car models.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))

3.1.1 Change the point shapes for the simple plot

There may be warning on this. The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values, but we have 7 models here.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

3.1.1 More for the simple plot

For the color, we can use both name and rgb. For the shapes, there are 25 built-in shapes in R. There are some seeming duplicates: for example, 0, 15, and 22 are all squares. The difference comes from the interaction of the colour and fill aesthetics.

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "#32a852", shape = 11, size =  2)

3.2 Facets

One way to add additional variables is with aesthetics. Another way, particularly useful for categorical variables, is to split your plot into facets, subplots that each display one subset of the data.

The argument of facet_wrap should be a formula, which you create with ~ followed by a variable name(this variable should be discrete/categorical)

# Demonstration using facets
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

To facet your plot on the combination of two variables, add facet_grid to your plot call. Here we combine two variables cyl(number of cylinders) and drv(the type of driven train, where f=front-wheel drive, r = rear wheel drive, 4 = 4wd)

The bottom left grids have no observations since there are no cars which are 4 or 5 cylinders with rear wheel drive.

# Demonstration of using the facet_grid() function
ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

If you prefer to not facet in the rows or columns dimension, use a . instead of a variable name, e.g.+ facet_grid(. ~ cyl). Run the demonstration below to get the idea.

# Demonstration of using the facet_grid() function
ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

4. Optional materials

If you want to make more advanced plots, you can learn this part. For example, the following two plots using the same x and y. They describe the same data with different visual object o represent data. In R, we say that they use different geoms.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Every geom function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument. However, not every aesthetic works with every geom. You could set the shape of a point, but you could not set the shape of a line. On the other hand, you could set the linetype of a line. geom_smooth() will draw a different line, with a different linetype, for each unique value of the variable that you map to linetype.

Here we see that there are three lines, each line represents one type of car driven train.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

If we want different color for each line or add more information on the graph. We may add more layers, that is, to add more geoms.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(
    mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv),
    show.legend = F
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

This, however, introduces some duplication in our code. Imagine if you wanted to change the y-axis to display cty instead of hwy. You would need to change the variable in two places, and you might forget to update one. You can avoid this type of repetition by passing a set of mappings to ggplot(). ggplot2 will treat these mappings as global mappings that apply to each geom in the graph. In other words, this code will produce the same plot as the previous code:

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg, mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point() + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

If you place mappings in a geom function, ggplot2 will treat them as local mappings for the layer. It will use these mappings to extend or overwrite the global mappings for that layer only. This makes it possible to display different aesthetics in different layers.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg, mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(color = class)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The same rule applies for other geoms

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg, mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(color = class)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_line()

We can even customize our plot by choosing which line we want to show in the end. For example, we only want the smooth line of SUV in our graph.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg, mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point(mapping = ggplot2::aes(color = class)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(data = dplyr::filter(ggplot2::mpg, class == "suv"), se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Take one more example

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::mpg, mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_point() + 
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(se = TRUE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

5. Statistical Transformations

Lets use diamonds data set, and lets first take a look at the data.

data("diamonds")

Lets make a bar plot first. It seems we only choose one variable cut.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut))

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut, fill = color))

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut, fill = cut))

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut, 
                                           fill = clarity,
                                           alpha=0.2))

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds, aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(alpha=0.2)

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds, aes(x = cut, color = clarity)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(fill = NA, position = "identity")

position = fill works like stacking, but makes each set of stacked bars the same height. This makes it easier to compare proportions across groups. Run the code block below for a demonstration.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "fill")

position = dodge places overlapping objects directly beside one another. This makes it easier to compare individual values

It is important to transform your data into long type when you want to plot bar chart side by side as below.

ggplot2::ggplot(data = ggplot2::diamonds) + 
  ggplot2::geom_bar(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "dodge")

6. Coordinate System

Coordinate systems are probably the most complicated part of ggplot2. The default coordinate system is the Cartesian coordinate system where the \(x\) and \(y\) positions act independently to determine the location of each point. There are a number of other coordinate systems that are occasionally helpful. * coord_flip() switches the \(x\) and \(y\) axes. This is useful (for example), if you want horizontal boxplots. It is also useful for long labels: it is hard to get them to fit without overlapping on the \(x\)-axis. Runt he code block below for a demonstration.
